Advanced Missing Value Strategy & Feature Optimization
Objective: Improve upon the baseline model (RMSE: 11.9661, R2: 0.6926) by testing more sophisticated imputation methods and optimizing the feature set.

1. IterativeImputer

• Results: MSE: 145.0197, RMSE: 12.0424, MAE: 7.1521, R2: 0.6886.

• Observation: Performance slightly decreased compared to the baseline. This suggests that the linear modeling used by IterativeImputer may have introduced noise or failed to capture non-linear relationships in the missing data.

2. KNNImputer (k=5)

• Results: MSE: 132.6779, RMSE: 11.5186, MAE: 6.5077, R2: 0.7151.

• Observation: Significant improvement across all metrics. KNN was better suited for this dataset, effectively capturing local similarities between records to fill missing values.

3. Feature Count Optimization

• Method: Evaluated performance using the top 10, 20, 30, 40, and 51 numerical features based on Mutual Information scores.

• Optimal Point: Identified an elbow at 40 features.

• Final Result: Optimized RMSE of 10.8254. Adding features beyond 40 showed diminishing returns.

Feature Engineering
Objective: Create novel temporal and interaction features to capture complex relationships in the audio data, evaluating them mathematically before model insertion.

1. Engineered Features & Mutual Information: Instead of blindly adding features, Mutual Information (MI) Regression was used to validate their predictive power against the target.

• `beat_to_groove_ratio`: Ranked #2 overall (MI Score: 2.345). Proved the hypothesis that the interaction between beat frequency and groove efficiency is a massive driver of the target.

• `intensity_to_duration`: Ranked #16 overall (MI Score: 2.062).

• `track_age_days`: Ranked #23 overall (MI Score: 1.644). Extracted absolute time from the timestamp, providing a strong historical trend signal absent in the cyclical features (season/weekday).

• `organic_density`: Ranked #41. Failed to break the top 40 threshold and was excluded from the pipeline to prevent noise.

2. Model Evaluation (Random Forest with New Features):

• Validation MSE: 119.0296

• Validation RMSE: 10.9101

• Validation MAE: 6.0164

• Validation R2: 0.7444

• Discussion: The engineered features caused a significant leap in $R^2$ (up to ~74.4%) and a massive drop in MAE (down to ~6.01). The model is now highly accurate on median predictions, proving the engineered ratios successfully exposed hidden core patterns in the data.

Upgrading the Modeling Strategy (XGBoost)
Objective: Fulfill the requirement to test and compare at least two different ML approaches by implementing Extreme Gradient Boosting (XGBoost) and comparing it against the Random Forest baseline.

1. Untuned XGBoost (Version 5.0):

• Method: Implemented an out-of-the-box XGBoost Regressor (500 trees, depth 6).

• Result: Severe overfitting. The validation RMSE spiked to 12.38 (worse than the initial baseline).

• Drawback Identified: Unlike Random Forest, Boosting algorithms aggressively target residuals and will quickly memorize training noise if not regularized.

2. Tuned XGBoost via RandomizedSearchCV (Version 5.2):

• Method: Implemented Early Stopping and a `RandomizedSearchCV` over a 3-fold cross-validation to find optimal hyperparameters (learning rate, max depth, subsample rates) across 20 iterations.

• Results: Validation MSE: 134.39, RMSE: 11.59, MAE: 7.34, R2: 0.71.

• Discussion & Comparison: The tuned XGBoost significantly improved upon the untuned version but ultimately failed to beat the Random Forest (RMSE: 10.91).

• Conclusion: The Random Forest's Bagging approach proved more robust for capturing the deep, non-linear relationships in the engineered features without requiring exhaustive hyperparameter tuning. The major drawback of XGBoost is its extreme sensitivity to hyperparameter configuration; a 20-iteration random search was insufficient to find a configuration that out-performed the deeply grown trees of the Random Forest.

Advanced Ensembling (Stacking Regressor)
Objective: Combine the strengths of Bagging (Random Forest) and Boosting (XGBoost) to achieve the highest possible predictive accuracy.

1. Methodology:

• Implemented a `StackingRegressor` using a 3-fold cross-validation scheme.

• Base Learners: The highly successful Random Forest (from Phase 2) and a regularized XGBoost model.

• Meta-Learner: A Ridge Regression model was selected to blend the base predictions. Ridge was chosen to prevent the meta-learner from overfitting or over-relying on a single base model.

2. Model Evaluation:

• Validation MSE: 115.8201

• Validation RMSE: 10.7620

• Validation MAE: 6.6577

• Validation R2: 0.7513

3. Discussion & Conclusion: The Stacking Ensemble successfully achieved the lowest RMSE (10.76) and highest R-squared (~75.1%) of the entire project, proving the efficacy of combining different algorithmic approaches. Interestingly, while the RMSE improved, the MAE increased slightly compared to the standalone Random Forest (6.01 to 6.65). This demonstrates the Ridge meta-learner's mathematical optimization: it traded a slight decrease in median accuracy to aggressively correct large outlier errors, ultimately producing a more robust and heavily penalized model.
